    {"parentUuid":"5ad9af80-5e3f-4583-8829-329e0f846f69","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a49dde84dd995ec5c","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01J5T5fDf21XYssdCZrsCGjJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The analysis is complete. Here is a summary:\n\n**File created:** `/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/experiments/algebraic/lthird_analysis.md`\n**File updated:** `/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/status/CLOSED_PATHS.md` (new entry added)\n\n## Key Findings\n\n**All four NFS-type approaches fail for pi(x).** The failures are structural, not technical:\n\n1. **Norm-based sieve** -- Counting integers representable as norms in Z[alpha] reduces to counting primes in residue classes. Each class requires its own L-function zero sum at cost O(x^{1/2+eps}). Failure mode: Equivalence.\n\n2. **Chebotarev density** -- Computing Frob_p requires knowing p (circularity). Even ignoring that, each field gives pi(x) only to within O(x^{1/2}) error, and combining k fields reduces error by only sqrt(k) -- need k > x to get exact answer. Failure mode: Circularity + Information loss.\n\n3. **Class group computation** -- h(K) encodes L(1, chi) which is an infinite Euler product over all primes. You cannot invert a product to recover individual terms. The L[1/2] algorithm for class numbers does not transfer to pi(x). Failure mode: Equivalence.\n\n4. **Artin L-functions** -- pi(x) depends only on zeta(s) zeros, not on other Artin L-functions. The Langlands trace formula is exactly the explicit formula in disguise. Failure mode: Equivalence.\n\n**Root cause:** NFS achieves L[1/3] because factoring is a *multiplicative search problem* -- find one relation x^2 = y^2 (mod N). Prime counting is an *additive summation problem* -- compute sum_{p <= x} 1. Smoothness-based decomposition, the engine of NFS, has no useful analog for counting. The answer: **no algebraic number theory technique can achieve better than O(x^{1/2+eps}) for pi(x)**, and the gap between L[1/3] and x^{1/2} at x = 10^100 is a factor of 10^{34}."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":355,"cache_read_input_tokens":36097,"output_tokens":539,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":355},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZjR3YsDL9LAPzSCkBfTN","type":"assistant","uuid":"df0e50d4-c0f4-46da-9fdc-e463f4b945a1","timestamp":"2026-04-04T21:09:10.516Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"a7d53bb6-087f-4e7d-81de-1d8a45f40cf3","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"sparkling-chasing-pascal"}
    
